{{Underline|fff}}
<Br><br>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Div style="border: 5px double white;padding: 3em;margin: 0.5em;">
<Div style="font-family: Shadows Into Light Two;text-align: center;font-size: 30px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
I / One{{Underline|fff}}Description
</div>
<Br>
{{Blurimage|file=JI Level 168.png|caption=The field viewed from a large house.}}
[[Level 183]], colloquially titled "Juvenile Imagination" or "Paper Houses," comprises a vast, colorless field under an unchanging, and overcast sky. The atmosphere is constantly in a state reminiscent of perpetual dusk, but no discernible light source defines the horizon.

The terrain is evenly flat but spatially inconsistent; linear traversal frequently results in paradoxical return, indicative of pronounced non-Euclidean geometry. There is no natural variation in elevation or landmark topology; only the monotonous sprawl of structures.

Everything within the level are made of white, and clean paper. Residential units dominate, and exhibit near-identical dimensions and placement, which suggests an even, if juvenile, symmetry. Occasionally, this homogeneity is disrupted by strangely large edifices: long paper hotels, monolithic apartments, and in rare instances: folded skyscrapers rising with improbable scale.

Surface textures usually feature oversized, and rudimentary illustrations drawn in coal or marker, likely simulating children's sketches. These include anthropomorphic figures, plants, simplified animals, and symbols. Some interiors possess furnishings not as physical structures but as two-dimensional drawings affixed to walls, which implies imaginative substitution over function.

Artificial light fixtures are frequently encountered: lamps, ceiling bulbs, and exterior sconces, but emit no measurable illumination. Instead, ambient brightness appears to emanate from the wanderer themselves, which creates a diffuse, and mobile glow whose source is undetermined.

Despite its aesthetic whimsy, the level exudes spatial dissonance and psychological unease.
</Div>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Br><br>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Div style="border: 5px double white;padding: 3em;margin: 0.5em;">
<Div style="font-family: Shadows Into Light Two;text-align: center;font-size: 30px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
II / Two{{Underline|fff}}Anomalies
</div>
<Br>
<Div style="font-family: Shadows into light two;text-align: center;font-size: 20px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
Digital Noise Effect{{Underline|fff}}</div>
<Br>
{{Blurimage|file=JI Level 168 2.png|caption=One of the well-known photo of the phenomenon.|align=left}}
A recurring perceptual phenomenon within [[Level 183]] is the '''Digital Noise Effect''', predominantly observed in individuals equipped with digital devices such as cameras, mobile phones, or audiovisual recorders. This anomaly manifests spontaneously and without clear environmental triggers.

During its onset, affected individuals report a gradually sharpening of vision, with the overlay of monochromatic digital static; reminiscent of pixelated interference or corrupted videos. This visual distortion is usually paired with an audible layer of broadband noise, similar to analog television static or disrupted signal output. Strangely, when recording devices are active during the occurrence, the interference is not limited to subjective experience; instead, it becomes visible in the footage itself, which effectively validated the occurrence.

Individuals undergoing the effect frequently describe mild hallucinatory symptoms, which include peripheral flickers, movement within non-moving objects, or the presence of looming silhouettes beyond their sight. These are commonly associated with a mild sense of unease, isolation, or impending harm.

The phenomenon is temporary, which usually lasts from thirty seconds to two minutes, and has no known long-term cognitive effects. However, repeated occurrence appears to induce heightened sensitivity to environmental irregularities, particularly in dim or enclosed areas of the level.

<Div style="font-family: Shadows into light two;text-align: center;font-size: 20px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
Crinkle Lag{{Underline|fff}}</div>
<Br>
A common and non-threatening phenomenon found throughout [[Level 183]] is known as '''Crinkle Lag'''. This effect usually occurs when an individual moves too quickly or makes sudden gestures within the environment, especially inside paper structures.

When triggered, the surroundings briefly respond with a delayed reaction. For example, opening a paper door may produce a noticeable pause before the door visibly reacts; sometimes with a soft, and delayed crinkle or rustling sound. Similarly, footsteps may emit sound a second later, or paper leaves may rustle after the air has slowed down.

The delay is not even. In some areas, it is barely noticeable, but in other areas, it can last up to five full seconds.

Importantly, '''Crinkle Lag''' does not harm individuals in any function. It is mostly reported as a mild nuisance or source of confusion, which occasionally results in missteps when doors or stairs do not behave as expected.

The effect fades when movement slows or when the individual returns to more open parts of the field. Its presence is strongest in enclosed spaces, particularly in tight paper corridors or dens that resemble blanket forts.

<Div style="font-family: Shadows into light two;text-align: center;font-size: 20px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
Childwritten Notes{{Underline|fff}}</div>
<Br>
<Div style="border-left: 5px double silver;padding: 2em;margin: 2em;">
1: Hello? Hello hello? Alright, good, the recorder’s finally running.<br>
2: You think this mission might get dangerous?<br>
1: I’ve got a feeling, yeah. Just being here already feels… off. And look at the ground; have you seen grass like that before?<br>
2: It looks like paper knives. Thin, sharp, and pointed in one direction.

(Their footsteps continue, stepping on the crusty papers of the place.)

(Rustling noises roar through them.)

1: Wait, this spot… haven’t we seen this already?<br>
2: Yeah. That carved pole, the paper chair, it’s all the same. We’ve circled back.<br>
1: Dammit! It’s been an hour and we’re just walking in loops. Nothing changes. Just this endless plain of paper scraps—<br>
2: Hold on. That wasn’t here before.<br>
1: Huh? What is it?<br>
2: A piece of paper. But this one’s different—<br>
1: Don’t start messing around—<br>
2: I’m serious. This one’s got writing on it. Notes. Looks deliberate.<br>
1: …Okay. That’s new.<br>
2: Let me pick it up. Give me a second.<br>

<div style="border: 5px double silver; padding: 2em; font-family: Mynerve;background: #222;box-shadow: 0 0 1em white;">
''Dear Daddy,''

''I don’t reely know where I am… and I don’t know where you are eether. Everythin’s too big, too quiet, too broken. But I wanted to tell you sumthin. Sumthin importent.
I finally did it.''

''Do you remmember the lil house I used to draw? The one with flouwers on the roof and the funny door? I found a place kinda like it. It’s not perfict, but it’s mine, just like I dreamd befor we got lost from each other. I even made a tiny gardin with sticks and shiny glass. I pretened you helped me plant it.''

''I hope you’re safe somewher. I hope your warm. I hope you don’t cry like I do sumtimes.
If you ever find this note… I mite already be <span style="word-spacing: 15px;letter-spacing: 5px;">gone  forever  sleepin</span>''
<div style="text-align:right;">''Your dotter,  Gena''
''I still don’t know how to spell my name rite.''
</div></div>

1: …Jesus.<br>
2: Yeah.<br>
1: Think she’s still out here?<br>
2: I don’t know.<br>
1: We better keep moving.<br>
2: Yeah. Let’s not get too attached to anything here. Not even words.

(Recording continues as the wind roars, louder this time with the rustlings of the papers. One of them pockets the note.)</div>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Br>

Randomly placed throughout the corners, closets, and crawlspaces of the paper houses in [[Level 183]] are small, and handwritten notes, which mostly appear to be composed by children. These notes are usually tucked beneath drawn furniture, pinned with folded tape to walls, or partially hidden between the layers of the paper structures themselves.

The handwriting varies, but usually displays signs of early literacy: reversed letters, inconsistent spelling, simple vocabulary, and emotional candor. The content of these messages ranges from mundane observations ("I saw a bird with no eyes on the walls") to more intimate expressions of fear, hope, or longing ("I miss Mommy" or "I'm hiding so they can't find me"). Some notes reference imaginary places, family members, or safe spots, which usually correlates with landmarks that do not exist elsewhere in the level.

Although the authors are unidentified, the sheer volume and distribution of these writings suggest a pattern. Some researchers propose that these notes are remnants of former wanderers, particularly lost children, but other people argue they are artifacts generated by the level itself, which are meant to simulate memory or preserve imagined narratives.

Of particular interest is that these notes appear before the '''Digital Noise Effect''' intensifies or during emotionally charged moments. In at least one documented case, a note was discovered addressed directly to a wanderer by name, although no evidence of prior contact with the writer could be confirmed.

Although the notes pose no known hazard, their psychological impact is visible. Many readers report feelings of nostalgia, melancholy, or a fleeting sense of familiarity, even when no personal connection exists.
</Div>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Br><br>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Div style="border: 5px double white;padding: 3em;margin: 0.5em;">
<Div style="font-family: Shadows Into Light Two;text-align: center;font-size: 30px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
III / Three{{Underline|fff}}Entities
</div>
<Br>
{{Blurimage|file=JI Level 168 4.png|caption=A rushed image of a [[Entity 36|Lighter]].}}
[[Level 183]] is commonly devoid of lifeforms, and many areas appear uninhabited. However, a small number of entities have been observed under specific environmental conditions, although encounters is rare.

[[Entity 13|Solarnoids]] have been found on rare cases, usually during prolonged wanderings near the outskirts of the level. [[Entity 36|Lighters]], similarly uncommon, are usually found within or around the larger structures; such as the paper hotels or tower-like buildings. Despite the fact that every light does not work, these entities appear to light up the surrounding environment, brighter than the light an individual emits.
</Div>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Br><br>
{{Underline|fff}}
<Div style="border: 5px double white;padding: 3em;margin: 0.5em;">
<Div style="font-family: Shadows Into Light Two;text-align: center;font-size: 30px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
IV / Four{{Underline|fff}}Entrances & Exits
</div>
<Br>
<Div style="font-family: Shadows into light two;text-align: center;font-size: 20px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
Entrances{{Underline|fff}}</div>
<Br>
{{Blurimage|file=JI Level 168 3.png|caption=A dinner-room styled room of a big hotel-like building.|align=left}}
Strangely, entrances to [[Level 183]] is predominantly facilitated through exits located within the 200–299 stratum of levels.
* Wandering into an achromatic section of [[Level 200]], [[Level 204]] will lead to [[Level 183]].
* A corridor with puerile illustrations within [[Level 207]] has been conclusively confirmed to direct into [[Level 183]].
* No-clipping into an achromatic expanse of grassy terrain in [[Level 208]] effectuates translocation to [[Level 183]].
* Traversing a trail overgrown with achromatic grass in [[Level 166]] may culminate in direct arrival at [[Level 183]].
* Physical contact with a parcel of achromatic crayons in [[Level 167]] instantaneously precipitates relocation to this level.

<Div style="font-family: Shadows into light two;text-align: center;font-size: 20px;text-shadow: 0 0 2px white;">
Exits{{Underline|fff}}</div>
<Br>
* Descending a concrete staircase in a hotel-like building, invariably leads to [[Level 187]].
* Opening a wooden closet outlined in green colors in a small house, results in immediate transition to [[Level 186]].
* Prolonged time spent within a room resembling a dining area may result in a transition to [[Level 185]].
* Following a drawn river or stream illustration is theorised to lead to [[Level 173]].
</Div>
